  <span id="freeText208211768406365450" style="display:none">Nora Roberts gives no fucks about timelines. When does Daniel's story take place? Assuming his grandkids are getting married in the late 90s (when those books were written) and he was 30 when he was married (and has been married for 40 years...and are newish grandpartents. However, he has to live for another 30 years or so to marry off the grandkids, eventually.) Anna is a feminist before it's cool and she's obviously one of the first female doctors around...and she wears long dresses...so 1930s?? There are telegrams, telephones, and cars, and I think some other things that seem too modern. I think it probably has to take place in the 1940s but with no mention of any war. Weird.<br /><br />Here's my best guess:<br />1910 - Daniel born<br />1940 - Daniel married<br />1941 or so - first kid<br />1970 or so - first kid married and pops out kid - around the time this story takes place. In this case, though, they've only been married 30 years.<br />1997 - grandkids start getting married, popping out kids<br /><br />So either they got married in the 1930s and Daniel is in his late 90s when he's matchmaking grandkids, or they got married in the 1940s and haven't been together for 40 years then this story happens. Or the whole timeline is shifted forward and the grandkids are getting married in a future with no internet/cell phones/whatever. Or they're a weird strain of accelerated-growth humans...<br /><br />The other story was pretty short and follows a typically Roberts conflict: What if a peace-loving woman falls for a soldier? Well, she obviously learns to appreciate him for who he is because patriotism.</span>
